<subSubSection pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1437,325,712]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,325,351]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
All coxae and femora entirely yellow (
<figureCitation box="[716,852,326,353]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1936,1960]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,860,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-242@21.[151,1435,860,1912]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 15. Habitus (upper, lateral view; lower, dorsal view) of species of the Colocasiomyia cristata subgroup.A, C. ecornuta sp. nov. ♂; B, C. grandis sp. nov. ♂; C, C. vieti sp. nov. ♂; D, C. cristata de Meijere ♂; E, C. sulawesiana Okada &amp; Yafuso ♂; F, C. kinabaluana sp. nov. ♂; G, C. kotana sp. nov. ♂; and H, C. matthewsi sp. nov. ♂. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766434" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766434/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Fig. 15M,N</figureCitation>
). A pair of processes on male abdominal sternite VI longer than 
<quantity box="[285,373,362,388]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" unit="mm" value="0.1">0.1 mm</quantity>
, proximally parallel, distally divergent (
<figureCitation box="[822,912,362,388]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1780,1804]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1757]" captionTargetId="figure-18@13.[151,1435,181,1757]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Male abdominal sternite VIs of Colocasiomyia colocasiae (Duda) (B in anteroventral view, C in lateral view), C. stamenicola (Carson &amp; Okada) (D in anterior view) and all species of the C. cristata subgroup (A in ventral view, E‒R in anterior view): A, C. ecornuta sp. nov.; E, C. grandis sp. nov.; F, C. vieti sp. nov.; G, C. cristata de Meijere; H, C. matthewsi sp. nov.; I, C. sulawesiana Okada &amp; Yafuso; J, C. kinabaluana sp. nov.; K, C. kotana sp. nov.; L, C. sabahana sp. nov.; M, C. sarawakana sp. nov.; N, C. pistilicola (Carson &amp; Okada); O, C. xenalocasiae (Okada); P, C. diconica (Toda &amp; Okada); Q, C. sumatrana sp. nov.; and R, C. leucocasiae sp. nov. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766420/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Fig. 9Q</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="44" lastPageNumber="45" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1437,325,712]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,397,423]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Description</emphasis>
(
<specimenCount box="[354,375,398,424]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount box="[431,453,398,424]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
; not repeating characters common to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Okada" baseAuthorityYear="1980" box="[879,1058,398,424]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Colocasiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xenalocasiae">
<emphasis box="[879,898,398,424]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[912,1058,398,424]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">xenalocasiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Head. Supracervical setae 9–11 per side. Eye with fine, sparse interfacetal setulae. Cibarial, medial sensilla 2–3 per side; posterior sensillum 1 per side. Supralateral seta outside prementum 1 per side.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1437,325,712]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Thorax. Prescutellar acrostichal setae absent. Apical scutellar setae nearer to each other than to basal scutellar seta.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1437,325,712]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
Abdomen. Male tergites: I and II medially pale grayish yellow, laterally dark grayish brown; III–VI nearly entirely dark grayish brown (
<figureCitation box="[474,583,614,641]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1936,1960]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,860,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-242@21.[151,1435,860,1912]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 15. Habitus (upper, lateral view; lower, dorsal view) of species of the Colocasiomyia cristata subgroup.A, C. ecornuta sp. nov. ♂; B, C. grandis sp. nov. ♂; C, C. vieti sp. nov. ♂; D, C. cristata de Meijere ♂; E, C. sulawesiana Okada &amp; Yafuso ♂; F, C. kinabaluana sp. nov. ♂; G, C. kotana sp. nov. ♂; and H, C. matthewsi sp. nov. ♂. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766434" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766434/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Fig. 15M</figureCitation>
). Female tergites variable in color: nearly entirely pale yellow or each tergite with grayish brown to dark gray bands on sublateral portions (
<figureCitation box="[840,943,650,677]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1936,1960]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,860,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-242@21.[151,1435,860,1912]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 15. Habitus (upper, lateral view; lower, dorsal view) of species of the Colocasiomyia cristata subgroup.A, C. ecornuta sp. nov. ♂; B, C. grandis sp. nov. ♂; C, C. vieti sp. nov. ♂; D, C. cristata de Meijere ♂; E, C. sulawesiana Okada &amp; Yafuso ♂; F, C. kinabaluana sp. nov. ♂; G, C. kotana sp. nov. ♂; and H, C. matthewsi sp. nov. ♂. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766434" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766434/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Fig. 15N</figureCitation>
). Male abdominal sternites III and IV longer than wide, rectangular (
<figureCitation box="[416,521,686,712]" captionStart="FIGURE 28" captionStartId="43.[151,250,1733,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,736,1709]" captionTargetId="figure-196@43.[151,1435,736,1709]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURE 28. Colocasiomyia sumatrana Toda &amp; Takano, sp. nov. (♂ and ♀ paratypes). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view; inset: surstylus); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766462" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766462/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Fig. 28A</figureCitation>
). Female abdominal sternites VI longer than wide (
<figureCitation box="[1094,1198,686,712]" captionStart="FIGURE 28" captionStartId="43.[151,250,1733,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,736,1709]" captionTargetId="figure-196@43.[151,1435,736,1709]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURE 28. Colocasiomyia sumatrana Toda &amp; Takano, sp. nov. (♂ and ♀ paratypes). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view; inset: surstylus); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766462" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766462/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Fig. 28B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766462" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5766462" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766462/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" startId="43.[151,250,1733,1757]" targetBox="[151,1435,736,1709]" targetPageId="43">
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1436,1733,1829]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,289,1733,1757]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">FIGURE 28.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Toda &amp; Takano" authorityName="Toda &amp; Takano" authorityYear="2021" box="[297,734,1733,1757]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Colocasiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sumatrana" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[297,564,1733,1757]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Colocasiomyia sumatrana</emphasis>
Toda &amp; Takano
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[745,827,1733,1757]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[745,827,1733,1757]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(♂ and ♀ paratypes). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view; inset: surstylus); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1437,1875,2010]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
Male terminalia. Epandrium pubescent except for anterior and ventral margins and anteroventral elongation, with approximately 3 setae on lateral to dorsal portion and 16–17 setae on ventral portion of each side (
<figureCitation box="[1320,1424,1911,1937]" captionStart="FIGURE 28" captionStartId="43.[151,250,1733,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,736,1709]" captionTargetId="figure-196@43.[151,1435,736,1709]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURE 28. Colocasiomyia sumatrana Toda &amp; Takano, sp. nov. (♂ and ♀ paratypes). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view; inset: surstylus); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766462" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766462/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Fig. 28C</figureCitation>
). Surstylus with 1–3 recurved, thick, trichoid setae apically and 1–2 minute setae subapically (
<figureCitation box="[1230,1336,1947,1973]" captionStart="FIGURE 28" captionStartId="43.[151,250,1733,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,736,1709]" captionTargetId="figure-196@43.[151,1435,736,1709]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURE 28. Colocasiomyia sumatrana Toda &amp; Takano, sp. nov. (♂ and ♀ paratypes). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view; inset: surstylus); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766462" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766462/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Fig. 28C</figureCitation>
). Cercus pubescent except for anterior margin and ventral 2/5, with approximately 25–27 setae (
<figureCitation box="[1126,1228,1983,2009]" captionStart="FIGURE 28" captionStartId="43.[151,250,1733,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,736,1709]" captionTargetId="figure-196@43.[151,1435,736,1709]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURE 28. Colocasiomyia sumatrana Toda &amp; Takano, sp. nov. (♂ and ♀ paratypes). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view; inset: surstylus); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766462" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766462/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Fig. 28C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1436,150,645]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
Female terminalia. Oviscapt about 5 times as long as wide, slightly curved downward, with 19–20 ovisensilla (
<figureCitation box="[160,260,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 28" captionStartId="43.[151,250,1733,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,736,1709]" captionTargetId="figure-196@43.[151,1435,736,1709]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURE 28. Colocasiomyia sumatrana Toda &amp; Takano, sp. nov. (♂ and ♀ paratypes). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view; inset: surstylus); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766462" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766462/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 28F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1436,150,645]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
